  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize the process of concealing illegally obtained money\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose penalties and criminal sanctions for money laundering activities\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Monetary fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Compliance with international anti-money laundering standards\n- Collaboration with global financial intelligence units\n\nThese statutes provide a comprehensive legal framework to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities across various financial sectors.",
